**In this post, I am going to talk about all the three approaches involved to solve this problem**

#1 Recursion

This solution is the most simplest one among three but yes it will give TLE due to its fairly exponential time complexity.... Not a suggested way but its surely the first step and the basic step to move towards DP i.e. optimised solution...
```
class Solution {
public:
    int climbStairs(int n) {
        //  Recursive

        if(n==0){
            return 1;
        }
        if(n==1){
            return 1;
        }
        if(n==2){
            return 2;
        }
        return climbStairs(n-1) + climbStairs(n-2);
    }
};
```

#2 Memoization (Top-Down)

An optimisation to the recursive approach... In this recursion is still present but here what we do is store the overlapping subproblems results in hand... as the main problem with recursive approach was that we were solving many sub problems repeatedly.... and so memoization comes into play... In this we store our results in a dp table(here its 1-D) and that would bring reduce the complexity O(n)

```
class Solution {
public:

    static int helper(int n,int *dp){
        if(n==0){
            return 1;
        }
        if(n==1){
            return 1;
        }
        if(n==2){
            return 2;
        }
        if(dp[n]!=-1){
            return dp[n];
        }
        return dp[n]=helper(n-1,dp) + helper(n-2,dp);
    }

    int climbStairs(int n) {
        //  Memoized

        int dp[n+1];
        for(int i=0;i<=n;i++){
            dp[i]=-1;
        }
        return helper(n,dp);
    }
};
```

#3 Tabulation (Bottom-up)

Same as memoization but here iteratively result is evaluated and this method is preferred over memoization due to various stack calls in Top down.... 

```
class Solution {
public:
