When thinking about this problem, I started by taking a look at how many possible ways you could climb up N stairs..

```
N = 1 -> [1] -> 1 way
N = 2 -> [1 + 1, 2] -> 2 ways
N = 3 -> [1+1+1, 1+2, 2+1] -> 3 ways
N = 4 -> [1+1+1+1, 1+1+2, 1+2+1, 2+1+1, 2+2] -> 5 ways
N = 5 -> [1+1+1+1+1, 1+1+1+2, 1+1+2+1, 1+2+1+1, 2+1+1+1, 1+2+2, 2+1+2, 2+2+1] -> 8 ways

```

At this point, it became pretty clear that a pattern was forming where the maximum number of ways you could climb up N stairs was equivalent to the MAX[N - 1] + MAX[N - 2].

However, if N == 1 or N == 2 this doesn't work, its simply 1 or 2.

Solution (recursive):
```
    public int climbStairs(int n) {
        if(n == 1) {
            return 1;
        } else if (n == 2) {
            return 2;
        }

        return climbStairs(n - 1) + climbStairs(n - 2);
    }
```

Thats really bad when N becomes large.. but we can use store the previous values in an array as we calculate to avoid the recursive call.

Solution (Dynamic Programming):

```
    public int climbStairs(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return 0;
        } else if (n == 1) {
            return 1;
        } else if (n == 2) {
            return 2;
        }
        int[] steps = new int[n];
        steps[0] = 1;
        steps[1] = 2;
        for (int i = 2; i < n; i++) {
            steps[i] = steps[i - 1] + steps[i - 2];
        }
        return steps[n - 1];
    }
```

